data <- readr::read_delim("wnv/metadata.tsv", delim="\t")
@

\subsection*{How long is the WNV genome?}

WNV is approximately 11k nt long. The samples pulled from NCBI GenBank have the following distribution of lengths. We can pick a length cut-off for the phylogenic tree:

<<fig.width=8, fig.height=3>>=
approx_length <- 11000
perc_length <- c(1.0, 0.90, 0.8, 0.75, 0.70)*approx_length

max_length <- max(data$length)
binwidth <- 200

data %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = length)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = binwidth, fill = "skyblue", color = "black") +
  theme_bw() +
  labs(
    x = paste("Sequence lengths (binwidth=", binwidth,")", sep=""),
    y = "Count",
    title = paste("Sequence lengths (all data = ",nrow(data),")", sep="")
  ) +
  geom_vline(xintercept = perc_length, linetype = "dashed", color = "red") +
  annotate("text", 
           x = perc_length+binwidth*1.5, 
           y = rep(15000, 5),
           label = paste0(round(perc_length), " (", c(100, 90, 80, 75, 70), "%)"),
           hjust = -0.1,
           angle = -90,
           size = 3,
           color = "blue")
@

\subsection*{How well sampled is WNV across time and space?}


<<fig.width=8, fig.height=4>>=
cdata <- data %>%
  subset(., !is.na(date)) %>%
  subset(., date !="XXXX-XX-XX") %>%
  mutate(
    date_adjusted = lubridate::date(gsub("-XX", "-01", date)),
    col_year = substr(date, 1, 4),
    col_mon = substr(date, 6,7),
    col_day = substr(date, 9,10)
  )

cdata %>% 
  ggplot(., aes(x=col_year, fill=region)) + 
  geom_bar() +
  theme_bw() +
  theme(
    axis.text.x = element_text(angle=90, vjust=1, hjust=1),
    legend.position = "bottom",
    legend.title = element_blank()
  ) +
  labs(
    title=paste("WNV entries with collection date (n = ",nrow(cdata),")", sep=""),
    x="Year", y="Count"
  )
@

The earliest samples seem to be from 1931. However, these are EF631122 and EF631123 and are supposedly collected in Illinois, USA, much earlier than the NY99 event. We might need to dig into publications that contain these GenBanks to check if this collection date is correct. Such as publication:

\begin{itemize}
\item Amore, G., Bertolotti, L., Hamer, G.L., Kitron, U.D., Walker, E.D., Ruiz, M.O., Brawn, J.D. and Goldberg, T.L., 2010. Multi-year evolutionary dynamics of West Nile virus in suburban Chicago, USA, 2005â€“2007. Philosophical Transactions of the Royal Society B: Biological Sciences, 365(1548), pp.1871-1878.
\end{itemize}

\subsection*{What lineages are available for WNV?}

\begin{itemize}
